Some of the darkest skies I’ve ever laid my eyes on in a remote desert wilderness. To get this shot I stacked multiple images of the night sky and the “Martian” foreground to create a scene that felt as ethereal as the galaxy itself. 

Summers almost over. Don’t forget to look up 🌌

Recently I spent some time at Many Glacier Lake in Montana. Despite overcast cloud cover, the lake was an enchanting sight. Grays and blues painted the vast stretch of water while the dramatic skyline added an extra touch of mystique. As the chilly winds brushed through, the lake mirrored the stormy heavens above, creating an otherworldly spectacle. The unspoiled wilderness, the whispering pines, and the rugged mountain terrain encompassing the area — all under the endless dome of the sky, was a sight to behold. Proof that nature's beauty is in every mood and color palette.

Morning glow on the Minarets 🌄

I hate camping in a tent but once a year I’ll head to the Sierras hauling 50 pounds of gear  in hopes of capturing a shot. Two days ago I hiked 7 miles up the John Muir trail to this spot and rolled out of my tent after have slept zero hours — because I never ever sleep when I’m tent camping — and saw an Alpen glow so magical that it made me forget all the creature comforts of 2023. 

Next year I’ll do the same thing because suffering for a day a year is okay if I get to pretend I’m a cowboy who is into camping & not just an Indian into photography.

Moonlight 🏔️🌝

This last moon cycle I decided to focus on an object that wasn’t the moon but rather something the moon illuminated. The full moon made these high mountain peaks shine as if it were twilight ✨

Every time there’s a full moon the media spins it to generate clicks and buzz. Truth is the general luminance of the moon remains the same whether it’s a full buck, blue supermoon or Moons Over My Hammy. 

Don’t get me wrong I think it’s great people are more interested in the moon’s phases. But moonlight is generally moonlight.

Ripples Through Time 

Every now and then, an adventure beckons me off the beaten path into the captivating realms of the uncanny and mesmeric. One such recent journey I experienced was a visit to the surreal geological marvel amidst the colossal sandy desert, known as White Pocket.

Situated in the desolate heart of the Vermillion Cliffs of Arizona & only accessible by a 4x4 vehicle , White Pocket portrays a strange yet marvelous array of swirling, knotted, and corrugated rocks that mimic melted plastic. Every turn, every nook and cranny in this labyrinth offers a different formation, a different color, a different texture that leaves you gasping at nature's beauty.  My visit was a testament to how breathtakingly beautiful and mind-bogglingly surreal our planet's landscapes can be.
There’s something magical about sharing the grandeur of Mother Nature with your dog, turning a simple hike into an extraordinary adventure. 🌲🐾🍃

Nature’s Sunroof

Every twist and turn felt like stepping into a beautifully intricate masterpiece of nature. The multi-hued canyon walls, etched by millions of years of wind and water, narrated a forgotten tale of our planet's history. The colors, lights, and textures of the sandstone were truly mesmerizing.

Recently I witnessed one of the most spectacular natural phenomena, a majestic lightning strike over the iconic Horseshoe Bend. As the sky turned dark and stormy, I set up my camera, unsure of what I would capture. And then, Mother Nature decided to put on a show. A brilliant bolt of lightning tore through the night, illuminating the entire landscape, It was as if time stood still. The raw power of nature, paired with the serene beauty of Horseshoe Bend, made for an awe-inspiring spectacle.

Havasupai Falls, the hidden gem in the heart of the Grand Canyon. The cascading turquoise waters against the fiery red rocks were simply breathtaking! This slice of paradise is a testament to Nature's grandeur and brilliance. 

So remote, so pure! This is nature at its finest: unspoiled paradise 💦🏜️

Had the most surreal experience trekking down to Mooney Falls. The canyon walls beautifully frame the rushing turquoise blue waters cascading 196 feet down. The climb is tough, but, the reward is worth it!

One of the best Auroral displays I’ve ever witnessed. About a week ago the sky exploded in a cocophany of color and movement. Deep purples, reds and greens were visible to the naked eye for hours on end. 

We are in the midst of a solar maximum, meaning solar storms will continue to remain intense. Keep your head up to the stars 🟣🟢

The idyllic village of Reine is located on the island of Moskenesøya and is often referred to as one of the most beautiful places in the world.

With its distinctive red cabins dotting the coastline, set against a backdrop of majestic mountains and turquoise waters, Reine is a haven of tranquility and untouched natural beauty.

The celestial symphony of colors known as the Northern Lights in Norway are extremely humbling. The shimmering curtains of green, pink, and violet dancing across the inky black Norwegian sky left me in absolute awe.

The Pillars of Creation are 7,000 light-years from Earth.

They are named so because the gas and dust are in the process of creating new stars, while also being eroded by the light from nearby stars that have recently formed.

Orca Whales! 

Shoutout @markgirardeau & @lawofthelandnsea & @pacificoffshore for making this happen 🤙🏾

I’ve waited 8 years to see Orca Whales in Southern California and lucked out on the final hour of an 8 hour search for these elusive creatures. 

What’s special about this pod of 10 is they rarely visit California and are extremely boat friendly. They were extremely curious and swam by and and said hi over and over and over again. 

I dunked my phone in a few times for footage and felt a dorsal fin graze my hand. An experience of a lifetime 🥹☺️

But first I want to share something I read today that really hit me and makes me feel grateful for family, friends and the small things : 

THE PARADOX OF OUR AGE

We have bigger houses, but smaller families; more conveniences, but less time.
We have more degrees, but less sense; more knowledge, but less judgements; more experts, but more problems; more medicines, but less healthiness.
We've been all the way to the moon and back; but have trouble crossing the street to meet the new neighbour.
We build more computers to hold more information to produce more copies than ever but have less communication.
We have become long on quantity, but short on quality.
These are times of fast foods but slow digestion;
Tall man, but short character;
Steep profits but shallow relationships.
It is a time when there is much in the window, but nothing in the room.

H.H. THE 14th Dalai Lama
